In Congress, battles broke out over anti-Semitism.

Republicans kicked out several prominent Democrats from influential Congressional committees at once. Under the blow were Adam Schiff - the organizers of the impeachments against Trump, Eric Svalvel - accused of having an intimate relationship with a Chinese intelligence officer. But a special scandal erupted around Ilhan Omar.

This Somali-born congresswoman has long resonated with poignant statements. For example, in 2018, Omar said that the 9/11 attacks were just some people who did something. And she called the real victims of the terrorist attacks the Muslims, who then faced a wave of Islamophobia.

Omar has also long characterized Israel as an "apartheid country." And compares Israeli and American soldiers in the Middle East with militants from Hamas and the Taliban. For this, the Republicans remove her from the intelligence committee - accusing Omar of anti-Semitism.

Democrats call sanctions against Omar a manifestation of "racism". However, they themselves began the epic of kicking out unwanted politicians from the committees - having done the same against Marjorie Taylor Green two years ago for contesting the election results. Now Green, on the contrary, has received important posts in the committees and began to really influence decision-making. But the ‚Äúanswer‚Äù has already arrived to the Democrats.

However, no matter how the Republicans now fight Omar, it is obvious that the views expressed by her are gradually becoming popular in the camp of the Democratic Party. Most Democrats already view Israel negatively. There are especially many critics of Israel among American youth.

Therefore, the general pro-Israel consensus that has existed in the US for decades will come apart at the seams in the future. After all, it is people like Omar who will determine the future of the Democratic Party - and under them, the issue of imposing US sanctions against Israel from theoretical will become quite practical.

U.S. Air Force officials said a corn plant project by Chinese company Fufeng Group in North Dakota posed a threat to the nation's national security. The firm had previously purchased 370 acres of farmland in Grand Forks, promising that the $700 million site would bring economic benefits to the region.  
  
The military department said the proposed project posed "a national security threat with short- and long-term risks of significant impact on U.S. Army operations in the area."  
  
The corn plant was planned to be built 19 kilometers from Grand Forks Air Force Base, home to intelligence units and unmanned aerial vehicles.  
  
Earlier, more than 5,000 local residents signed a petition aimed at preventing the construction of the farming project. At that time, the city government supported the Chinese investors, but in the new reality, the mayor's office opposed the Fufeng Group. The administration said they would block the construction by refusing to issue a permit.  
  
"The federal government has asked the city to help stop the project because geopolitical tensions have increased significantly since the initial announcement of the project," said Grand Forks Mayor Brandon Bochenski.  
  
Fufeng USA Chief Operating Officer Eric Chutorash responded by assuring that the plant would not be used for spying or harming the United States.
